text:
Visited @changiairport T3 today to meet the staff and workers, including taxi drivers, immigration officers and the medical staff. They are all working hard to keep our airport up and running during this challenging time.

The travel industry has been hit hard by COVID-19. Changi Airport is on the frontline. Despite this, I found our workers in good spirits. I left the airport heartened by their professionalism and commitment. Thank you for your hard work and dedication, keeping Singapore open for business!

We will ensure the safety of our workers, and enable them to do their jobs. Once again, letâ€™s stay strong and united and we will overcome this challenge. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether ([1] Photo by me; [2-6] MCI Photos by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on February 14, 2020. May be an image of 4 people.
text:
Very encouraged to read your messages supporting our healthcare team on Valentine's Day. This camaraderie with fellow Singaporeans will see us through the COVID-19 situation. On Total Defence Day today, let us stay united and watch out for one another. When the Public Warning System sirens sound later at 6.20pm, think about what you can do to help keep Singapore strong together. â€“ LHL (Photo by me)

@WeAreTotalDefence

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on February 18, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
This yearâ€™s Budget has extra significance. It provides critical support for Singaporeans and our economy as we deal with the COVID-19 outbreak.â € â €

We are able to do this because of our fiscal prudence and discipline over many years. Together, we have put aside enough to cope with a rainy day like this.â € â €

The Stabilisation and Support Package for workers and businesses will help tide them through the immediate term. The Care and Support Package will assure families and households. Meanwhile, we must continue to steward our resources and strengths, so that we are ready to grow again when the outbreak ends. â € â €

While we deal with this outbreak, let us continue to look out for one another, and keep building Singapore together. â €
You can find out more at the MOF Budget website: www.singaporebudget.gov.sgâ €
â €
â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#SGBudget2020â €

text:
A special music video of Home, performed by the @singaporechineseorchestra in tribute to our healthcare and frontline workers.

Glad the arts community is doing its part to rally Singaporeans during the COVID-19 outbreak. The current measures to limit the spread of the disease have spurred arts groups to consider creative alternatives, such as digital performances.

The best advice from local artists â€“ let the arts lift your spirits and donâ€™t be discouraged. Listen to music, read, dance or watch a play. Above all, stay strong and continue to live your life calmly. â€“ LHL

#SingaporeTogether

text:
Did a #jalanjalan at Jurong Bird Park a few weekends back. Our local attractions and businesses have taken a hit from the COVID-19 outbreak. But I was happy to see the staff in good spirits, working hard for both visitors as well as the birds.â €
â €
In the recent Budget, tourism is one of the sectors getting additional support. We will work closely with businesses and union leaders to ensure that workers are protected during this downturn.â €
â €
Meanwhile, it's a good time to visit (or re-visit) our local attractions. @jewelchangiairport has waived entrance fees to its canopy park till end March. If youâ€™re worried about travel restrictions, consider a staycation at a local hotel. Above all, let us go about our lives as normally as possible. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(Photos by me)

text:
Dr S Vasoo, who helps me out in Teck Ghee, has formed the Teck Ghee CARE Task Force to coordinate efforts to keep our residents safe from COVID-19. The task force will identify residents affected by this current crisis, particularly the elderly and vulnerable, and help them get financial, employment, health and hygiene support.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The task force brings together all the RCs in Teck Ghee, together with my Youth Networks, two Community Club Management Committees, Citizens' Consultative Committee, and AMKFSC Community Services. It is in these challenging times that the Singapore spirit shines brightest. Let us continue to look out for one another, especially those who need some extra help. Together, we will win this battle against the virus. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(The first meeting of the Teck Ghee Task Force on Thursday evening. / Photo by Teck Ghee Community Club)

text:
Today is #InternationalWomensDay. It is a day specially designated to recognise womenâ€™s contributions, and their vital and highly appreciated roles in our lives. In this COVID-19 outbreak, many women are on the frontlines safeguarding Singaporeansâ€™ health, and taking care of COVID-19 patients.

But while they are doing their jobs, dutifully keeping Singapore safe, they are also carrying on with equally important roles as mothers, wives, grandmothers, daughters, and more. #SuperSHEroes is an apt name indeed, for all that they do!

Do join me in showing your appreciation for the SuperSHEroes in your life. Hereâ€™s wishing all women a happy International Womenâ€™s Day! â€“ LHL

text:
Visited Yio Chu Kang this morning to see how everyone was coping with COVID-19. Glad to see many out and about, going about their usual Sunday morning activities at Ang Mo Kio 628 Market and Food Centre. Some were concerned about the outbreak, but they knew about our preventive measures â€“ starting with greeting one another without shaking hands!

Many thanks to @kohpohkoon for his good work as Advisor, and the grassroots leaders and volunteers doing their best to help residents. Really enjoyed the warm welcome from everyone and look forward to being back to lim teh-o kosong! â€” LHL

text:
The annual Sakura Matsuri is back at @gardensbythebay. Took in the beautiful pink and white cherry blossoms on a #jalanjalan on Sunday, along with a performance of Japanese taiko drums.

Cherry blossom season is a highlight of the Japanese calendar. These iconic flowers are popular with Singaporeans and other tourists too. But like so many events, the Matsuri has been affected by the COVID-19 outbreak.

We are lucky to have sakura blossoming on our sunny island. Itâ€™s a good time to visit â€“ children under 12 will get free admission during the March school holidays. Singapore residents will enjoy 50% off admission tickets and free parking till 22 March 2020. Bring your cameras! ğŸŒ¸ğŸŒ¸ğŸŒ¸ â€“ LHL (Photos by me)

text:
It is five weeks since I spoke about the COVID-19 situation in Singapore. So it is timely to update Singaporeans again on the medical, economic and psychological outlooks of the situation.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Today, the @WHO officially declared the COVID-19 outbreak a pandemic. This means that while the situation in Singapore remains under control, the COVID-19 threat will be with us for a long time. We cannot be complacent.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
There are some baseline precautions we must get used to, like maintaining good personal hygiene and not holding large gatherings. We must also plan ahead in case a major outbreak happens in Singapore, like in South Korea or Italy.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
If a major outbreak happens, we will need more stringent social distancing measures, such as suspending schools and compulsory telecommuting. These will slow down the rate of transmission and prevent our healthcare system from being overwhelmed.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Already our economy has been seriously impacted, so we are working on a second stimulus package to support businesses and workers.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Singaporeâ€™s response to COVID-19 has been recognised by WHO and the international community. This is through the efforts of many Singaporeans, from the frontline staff to all of us keeping #SGclean. I thank all Singaporeans who are dealing with this calmly and responsibly. We must keep up our efforts, and remain #SGUnited.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
You can watch my address in English, Malay and Chinese on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my bio). â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
This morning, I held a dialogue with grassroots leaders on COVID-19 and what lies ahead for Singapore. This was a follow up to my TV broadcast on Thursday.

Fighting COVID-19 is difficult enough. But we also need to deal with COVID-19â€™s enormous impact on our economy.

Yesterday, the Government released the report of the Electoral Boundaries Review Committee's (EBRC), which the Committee had just completed.

The General Elections must take place before 21 April 2021. They can only be called after the electoral registers are updated. This will take about a month.

When to hold elections? That depends on the situation, and the outlook.

Singapore faces grave and extended challenges.

We canâ€™t tell when the pandemic will end, but it will likely last at least this year, and quite possibly longer.

The economic hit will likely be more serious than the Global Financial Crisis, and longer-lasting too, even beyond the end of the pandemic.

I fully expect things to get more serious before they start getting better.

We have two choices. Either hope and pray that things will stabilise before the end of the term so that we can hold elections under more normal circumstances â€“ but we have no certainty of that.

Or else call elections early, knowing that we are going into a hurricane, to elect a new government with a fresh mandate and a full term ahead of it, which can work with Singaporeans on the critical tasks at hand.

If we have to hold elections before COVID-19 is over, we will take all the precautions necessary, so that parties can campaign effectively, and people can vote safely.

At stake are jobs, businesses and lives.

Which way to go, and the elections date, will depend on what will best see Singapore through this major crisis.

COVID-19 may well turn out to be the crisis that defines this generation of Singaporeans. We must gird ourselves to overcome this together, and show the world what Singapore can do. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited (MCI Photos by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on March 17, 2020.
text:
Last night, Malaysia announced that it would impose a Movement Control Order to combat the spread of COVID-19. This was not surprising, as many other countries have already imposed similar lockdowns.â €
â €
Prime Minister Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin and I discussed the situation on the phone today. I told him that I understood the reasons why he had made this move, and wished Malaysia success in containing the outbreak. I was happy to hear his reassurance that the flow of goods and cargo between Singapore and Malaysia, including food supplies, would continue.â €
â €
However, Malaysians living in Johor but working in Singapore will have to comply with the Malaysian lockdown. This will prevent them from commuting daily, at least for the time being. We are therefore working out arrangements with our companies to help these Malaysian workers stay in Singapore temporarily, if they would like to do so.â €
â €
We also agreed to appoint Senior Ministers on both sides â€” SM @teocheehean and Datoâ€™ Sri Ismail Sabri â€“ to coordinate our responses to the COVID-19 outbreak, particularly on measures where we can work together, or where the actions of one country will affect the other. They are already in touch, but it may take a couple of days for arrangements to be worked out and to settle down.â €
â €
Meanwhile, I am happy to see that in the supermarkets, while the queues are longer than usual, people are taking it in their stride and only buying what they need. We need not worry, as we have prepared for such an eventuality, and have plans in place to cope. Glad that Singaporeans are calm, united and resilient as we solve the problems at hand. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#SGUnitedâ €
â €
(The Causeway from above. Taken in 2017 during my visit to Putrajaya. / Photo by me)

text:
Last week, I dropped in on a trial run of the #BYOBClean programme, which is giving each household up to 500ml of water-based hand sanitiser, for free. You have to bring your own bottle to be filled up. Itâ€™s a timely initiative by the @temasekfoundationcares, to make sure no one is left behind in this fight against COVID-19.â €
â €
By now, households in Teck Ghee (and across Singapore) should have received pamphlets informing you of your collection date (the dates are staggered, to avoid overcrowding). You can go to https://stayprepared.sg/ to see where to bring your bottle to fill with hand sanitiser. â €
â €
Do look out for your pamphlets in the mail, and letâ€™s keep our hands clean! â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(A trial run of the #BYOBClean programme at Teck Ghee CC last Sunday. / MCI Photo by Chwee)

text:
Visited Teck Ghee Block 341 Market and a few families in Teck Ghee this morning, to see how everyone is coping. â €
â €
People were going about their activities, but making an effort to keep a safe distance. We are not quite there yet â€“ it was a peak time for the market, and it was more crowded than we would like to see. But people were conscious of COVID-19. Nearly everyone remembered not to offer to shake hands. A few wore masks, perhaps because they were not well.â €
â €
The pandemic is escalating rapidly around the world. Our own situation here is under control, but we are seeing quite a few new cases among Singaporeans and residents returning from abroad. There is a significant risk that they may infect others and start new clusters. We must do our utmost to prevent this. That is why returnees are being issued stay-home notices. If you are a returnee, please observe the notice strictly to protect others, and help us fight COVID-19. â €
â €
In these volatile times, everyone needs to remain vigilant and socially responsible, and adhere to all measures in place to keep Singapore safe. If we all do our part, we can ride out this storm together. â€” LHLâ €
â €
#SGUnitedâ €
#SingaporeTogetherâ €
â €

text:
Diplomacy in the time of COVID-19.

Held a virtual bilateral meeting with Australian PM @scottmorrisonmp via video conferencing today. While COVID-19 has certainly made travelling harder or even impossible altogether, technology can bridge the gap and enable us still to communicate with one another and get things done.

PM Morrison and I had a candid and fruitful discussion on the COVID-19 situation, our extensive economic cooperation, and sustainability. We also witnessed the signing of a treaty on military training and two MOUs on Artificial Intelligence and Data Innovation.

Singapore and Australia enjoy close and multifaceted ties, with warm people-to-people ties. Australia is a popular destination for Singaporeans â€“ not just for holidays and visiting friends, but also for studying. The SAF trains in Australia and our two armed forces have a long history of cooperation. I am confident that we will deepen our bilateral relationship further in the future. â€“ LHL (MCI Photos by Lee Jia Wen)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on March 27, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Sat down with local media today to talk about the Resilience Budget that @hengsweekeat announced in Parliament yesterday, and what lies ahead as the COVID-19 pandemic turns the world upside down.

We are heading into the storm with a major $55 billion package to help save jobs and businesses, support households, and keep our economy going. If the situation worsens, we are ready to do more.

The impact on our economy has been huge. This is only the second time ever we are drawing on our reserves. The last time was for the Global Financial Crisis in 2009. We will be drawing up to $17 billion to fund the support measures, more than triple what was drawn in 2009.

I have no illusions that this will be all we need. Nobody can tell what lies ahead. COVID-19 has shown starkly how vulnerable we are, and how our existential threats essentially remain the same, despite Singapore going from third world to first. The COVID-19 pandemic will be the formative experience for this generation of Singaporeans. If we remain vigilant, resolute, and united, I am confident we will get through this together.

You can watch the full interview here on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile) â€“ LHL

#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Zinkie Aw)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 03, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Since COVID-19, we have responded to the crisis calmly and systematically, planning ahead and adjusting our measures as the situation changed. The current situation is under control, but we want to take a few more steps now.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I gave my third televised update today on the current situation. You can watch it on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Let me reassure Singaporeans that our food supply is secure and adequate. Buy just what you need, and share any extra you have with those who need it. Letâ€™s stay calm and united during this challenging period. â€“ LHL

I was invited to share about Singaporeâ€™s efforts to fight COVID-19. Singapore will do our part, but it is not our battle alone. COVID-19 is a crisis that requires all countries to fight together. Singapore looks to the WHO to continue providing leadership and coordinate an effective global response. Together, we will overcome this. â€“ LHL

text:
Prime Minister @jacindaardern and I spoke on the phone this afternoon. We updated each other on how we are managing COVID-19 in Singapore and New Zealand. We are both implementing strict circuit breaking measures, to break transmission of the virus and squeeze the cases down.

PM Ardern shared that after New Zealand implemented their measures, numbers only started to come down on Day 11. We are only in Day 3 and still have a long way to go. If we all comply strictly, as the New Zealanders have done, hopefully by our Day 11 we too will see positive results.

PM Ardern and I also discussed how we can support each other during this time, including keeping supply chains intact between the two countries. Both Singapore and New Zealand will continue to do our part in this global fight against COVID-19.

At home, @masagosz has announced that enforcement officers will now immediately take down the particulars of anyone breaching the measures. More details on his Facebook post today. We cannot wait to save lives. Please do your part today. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited (Meeting PM Jacinda Ardern during her official visit to Singapore last year. / MCI Photo by Kenji Soon)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 09, 2020.
text:
Today is Good Friday, a day of fasting, prayer, and penance as Christians reflect on the crucifixion and death of Jesus Christ. This spirit of solemnity continues as Christians await the resurrection on Easter Sunday.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
It has been a difficult time for people of faith, including Christians here and elsewhere in the world. They have been unable to hold their usual services because of COVID-19 measures. However, these measures are essential to protect all of us, Christians and non-Christians alike. I am heartened that most Churches have introduced online services, and hope many will continue to find solace in prayer, and be united in spirit.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I wish all Christians a blessed and healthy Easter weekend, and that you will find joy in your hearts amid the simple celebrations. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI photo by Betty Chua)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 10, 2020.
text:
Posted a message on our current COVID-19 situation in English, Chinese and Malay on my Facebook Page, Telegram channel, and the PMO YouTube channel. Please share with your families and friends, especially older Singaporeans.

We saw our largest daily number of COVID-19 cases so far yesterday. Many were from foreign worker dormitories. My message explains what we are doing to contain the spread in the dorms, and protect the health and welfare of the foreign workers. We will do our utmost to take care of them.

The number of cases outside the dorms also continues to rise. This is precisely why we needed the circuit breaker. We need everyone to take it very seriously â€” stay home and stop socialising with others. If we do not observe this strictly, all our inconvenience, pain and sacrifice will all be in vain.

In the video I also appeal to older Singaporeans to stay at home, for your own safety.

The next few weeks will be tough. We have to get through them before the sun will shine over us again. Till that day comes, please stay home. â€“ LHL

#StayhomeforSG
#SingaporeTogether
#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 12, 2020.
text:
The different South Asian ethnic communities all have long histories in Singapore. Our largest group is Tamil, but we also have thriving Malayalee, Sikh, and Bengali communities. The Sikhs will be celebrating Vaisakhi, while the others will be marking their new years tomorrow.

I took the photo of the Silat Road Sikh Temple one evening in March 2015, after visiting my father who was then hospitalised in SGH. It was beautifully lit, a serene and inspiring presence at a time of worry and sadness. I thought it would not be out of place to share it now. We are battling COVID-19, and thinking about those among us who are ill with the disease.

The Sri Perumal temple photo was taken in October 2016, on a jalan jalan in Little India to see the Deepavali light up. I am not sure when we will be able to do light ups again, but we will keep the light of confidence and hope shining bright in our hearts.

Wishing all Sikhs a happy Vaisakhi, Malayalees a happy Vishu, Bengalis a happy Pohela Boishakh, and Tamils a happy Puthandu! â€“ LHL (L: Gurdwara Sahib Silat Road, or Silat Road Sikh Temple; R: Sri Perumal Temple, or Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple / Photos by me)

text:
The human spirit will survive and prevail.

You may have seen videos of orchestras that have used technology to continue creating music together, despite being on stay home notice or under lockdown.

Here at home, @macpherson_philharmonic performed a beautiful rendition of â€œThe Lightâ€, composed by local songwriters @jarrellhuang and @jjneo_ in tribute to those on the COVID-19 frontline.

Even as we stay home to protect ourselves and others, we can find ways and means to make the show go on, and bring joy to those around us. Things are uncertain now, but there is light at the end of the tunnel, and we must stay united and persevere. â€“ LHL 
#StayhomeforSG
#SingaporeTogether
#SGUnited

After the morning session with just @asean leaders, we resumed in the afternoon with the ASEAN Plus Three Summit. This included all 10 ASEAN member states plus China, Japan, and Korea.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I called on my counterparts to work together to mitigate the economic damage caused by COVID-19 and recover to a sustainable new normal. I also urged them to sign the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership (RCEP) this year to boost trade and investment flows.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I hope that todayâ€™s meeting will spur cooperation between ASEAN and the Plus Three countries. â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 21, 2020.
text:
We are now two weeks into our circuit breaker. I will be giving an update on where we are now and what we need to do next at 5pm today on TV and radio. You can also watch it â€˜liveâ€™ on my Facebook page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong).â €
â €
This is an uncertain and worrying time for many of us, especially with the large number of cases in the migrant worker dorms. Our teams have been working hard to contain the spread of COVID-19 in the dorms, and look after the well-being of our migrant workers.â €
â €
I urge everyone to persevere with the circuit breaker measures, and continue to help one another through this outbreak. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#SGUnitedâ €
#SingaporeTogetherâ €
â €
(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 21, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
It is two weeks since our COVID-19 circuit breaker started. I thank you all for complying with the restrictions. While community cases have fallen, we still need to bring their number down decisively. We also want to make sure that if any cases leak from the migrant worker population into the wider community, we can detect and contain them.

That is why we are tightening the circuit breaker measures, e.g. thinning out crowds at hot spots like wet markets, and closing more workplace premises, till 4 May. We will also extend the circuit breaker itself to 1 June.

I know that this has not been an easy time. The circuit breaker is working, but we need to do a little bit more, and for a bit longer. Let us all do our part to beat the virus, break the chain of transmission, and overcome this together.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). â€“ LHL 
#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether

MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 22, 2020.
text:
Today is #EarthDay, and this year marks its 50th anniversary.

This yearâ€™s celebration happens amidst the COVID-19 pandemic. Singaporeans, like people across the world, are staying home in an effort to stop the spread of this disease. But thanks to technology, we can still enjoy the breathtaking beauty of our shared home through virtual tours and amazing tools like Google Earth.

As glum as things seem now, COVID-19 will eventually pass. But the wicked problem of climate change will still be with us, and it will be even harder to tackle. It is sobering to think that if we do not succeed in slowing down climate change, these virtual tours may be all future generations have to remind them of what was lost because we did not take action sooner.

Singapore cannot stop climate change by ourselves. It needs a global effort. But we will do our bit. Each of us must do our bit too, through small and sustainable steps, for example by wasting less food, choosing more energy efficient options, and recycling more. Let us all do our part to protect our Earth. â€“ LHL (Taken at @gardensbythebay recently. / Photo by me)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 23, 2020.
text:
Tomorrow marks the start of the holy month of Ramadan, the fasting month for Muslims.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Fasting month this year will be markedly different. There will be no communal Terawih prayers, because mosques are all closed. Many would also be unable to break fast with their close family and friends, as they usually do. I hope you understand why the circuit breaker restrictions are being extended, to stamp out new COVID-19 transmissions and protect all of us.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I am glad that MUIS is providing many online resources, such as SalamSG TV to help foster the Ramadan spirit.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
To all our Muslim friends, I wish you a blessed and fulfilling fasting month. May this Ramadan be a time of quiet reflection and prayer, together with your immediate families. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(The majestic Sultan Mosque and the quiet Arab Street area during the circuit breaker period. / MCI Photo by Fyrol)â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 23, 2020. May be an image of 2 people.
text:
Spoke with PM @narendramodiÂ on the phone this evening. We discussed the COVID-19 situations in our two countries. Singapore is in the midst of the circuit breaker. India implemented a nationwide lockdown since late March, not a simple decision in a huge country of 1.3 billion people.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I thanked PM Modi for Indiaâ€™s help when we brought home some Singaporeans from India recently. I assured him that we will care for Indian migrant workers here, just as we care for Singaporeans. The migrant workers made personal sacrifices to come to work here. They have made many contributions to Singapore, so we have a responsibility for them.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Appreciate PM Modiâ€™s affirmation of our efforts in looking after the migrant workers, and his assurance that they will not forget this.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
India and Singapore are strategic partners with extensive economic ties. We agreed to work together on the challenges posed by the pandemic, keep supply chains intact, and keep essential supplies flowing. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(PM Modiâ€™s official visit to Singapore in June 2018. / MCI Photo by Kenji Soon)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 28, 2020. May be an image of text that says '20,000 daily meals throughout 30 days of Ramadan. be part of our $3m giving goal. êµ¬ rlafoundations SGUNITED BUKA PUASA For more info visit bukapuasa.sg'.
text:
COVID-19 has not diminished the spirit of Ramadan.â €
â €
#SGUnited Buka Puasa is a ground-up initiative to provide meals to our healthcare frontliners and their families, as well as other families in need throughout the month of Ramadan. MUIS delivers 10,200 break fast meals to 4,000 zakat recipients daily.â €
â €
This is a collaborative effort by MUIS, Malay Chamber of Commerce & Industry, @rlafoundationsg, @RosesofPeace, and @pafrenz. They have received tremendous support and generous contributions from the community.â €
â €
My thanks to all who have supported the project. So far they have raised 24% of their target amount. If you would like to contribute to this good cause, do visit: https://go.gov.sg/bukapuasasg. No amount and no effort is too small. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#SingaporeTogetherâ €
#SGTeguhBersatu

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 29, 2020. May be an image of 2 people.
text:
Colombian President @ivanduquemarquez and I spoke on the phone this morning. Naturally, we talked about COVID-19.

Singapore is grateful to the Colombian government for clearing the export of face masks to Singapore early in the outbreak.

Like Singapore, Colombia is using technology, including a â€œCoronApp-Colombiaâ€ mobile app which disseminates official information on the virus.

Despite being on opposite sides of the Pacific, Singapore and Colombia can cooperate and learn from each other, as we tackle the present challenges and prepare for the long recovery ahead. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited (I missed meeting President Duque in Davos in January. Minister @lawrencewongst had met him in Medellin, Colombia in July 2019. / Photo by @mndsingapore)

image_desc: Photo shared by Lee Hsien Loong on April 29, 2020 tagging @ntucsingapore.
text:
We canâ€™t hold the usual May Day Rally tomorrow because of COVID-19. Instead, I will broadcast my May Day speech tonight at 7:30pm. You can watch it on my Facebook Page, the PMO YouTube channel or on free-to-air TV.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In this crisis, it is vital for our unions, employers, and the Government to work together to help workers and families overcome these difficult times.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
If you need something to unwind after my speech, the @jazzassociation_sg and its YouTube channel will be live-streaming a â€˜Jass@Homeâ€™ online concert at 8.30pm. This marks the UNESCO International Jazz Day, which commemorates jazz and its role uniting people from all around the world.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Led by jazz maestro @jeremymonteiro, the concert will feature the evergreen folk song â€œSingapuraâ€ as a tribute to our frontline workers, and a special performance by Grammy award winner Randy Brecker on the trumpet.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I hope you will tune in to both events tonight! â€“ LHL â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(PMO Photo by Alex Qiu)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong in NTUC Singapore with @ntucsingapore. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'ntuc National Trades Union Congress'.
text:
#MayDay is usually a joyous occasion to celebrate the achievements of our workers and unions. But amidst COVID-19, this yearâ€™s event is more sombre.

May Day is an appropriate moment to thank our brothers and sisters, especially those on the front lines, and those performing essential services. You have kept Singapore going, and far exceeded the call of duty.

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

Our forefathers had the foresight to put aside reserves for emergencies like this. We too have to keep an eye on the future, and work together to make sure Singapore emerges stronger from COVID-19.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). â€“ LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
#EveryWorkerMatters (MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on April 30, 2020.
text:
COVID-19 has forced us to adapt to a new normal. During this circuit breaker, many of us have gotten used to a new normal of telecommuting and ordering goods online. This has increased demand, and created new opportunities for business. Some industries, like retail, may never be quite the same again.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This has been happening all along, though not so suddenly as now. New industries are constantly emerging, and we must be ready for them. 50 years ago who could have imagined a job as a social media manager, or in biotech?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I said in my #MayDay speech yesterday that we are determined to help companies prepare for the new operating environment, and to retrain workers for the new jobs available. We canâ€™t save every job, but we will look after every worker, and their families too.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I wish everyone a safe and meaningful #LabourDay. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
#EveryWorkerMatters
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(A shuttered shop in Orchard Road at the beginning of the circuit breaker period. / MCI Photo by Fyrol)â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

I am juggling a lot working from home and teaching my kid at the same time that it is taking a critical toll on my mental and physical health.
Closing school leads many people unemployed in an effort to take care of children during working hours, which eventually hit already dire economy situation even harder. Keeping school closed has to be considered very carefully taking all factors into consideration. In addition, every countries vary with respect to efficiency of closure of school. We cannot just follow other countries's case without taking into a unique Singaporean demographical charactor. For instance, Italy and UK that closed school have high rate of elderly population and two-thirds of workable adults live with their parents, which makes often three generations live in one household where normally grandmother take care of children when adults work. 
For these European countries, closing school was a necessary measure taken  to stop the spread of virus through children to the vulnerable old.
If Singapore keep closing school, many households will have to hire Foreign Domestic Helper, which result in more outside mingling that has to be minimized at this stage, let alone those who cannot afford will end up losing their jobs with prioritizing child care at home.
Lastly, even if we close the school for little one, kids are kids and they will run around and mingle with neighborhood' childreb who you don't even  know their travel history. Conversely, at school they control who they interact with by handing out travel declaration forms in advance and putting those unwell in quarantine under the strong supervision of designated teacher.
In nutshell, I have heard that there has been no single case children were spreader of virus and closing school will do more harm than good. Opening school will help to stop all this emotional, mental and physical agony that it has put and bring children opportunities to learn better with social and emotional interaction with other children and teachers. image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on May 06, 2020.
text:
Today is Vesak Day. It marks the birth, enlightenment and attainment of nirvana of Buddha. It is the most significant day of the Buddhist calendar.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Devotees will not be able to pray and present offerings at the temples this year because of COVID-19 measures. But I am sure they will find ways to practise love, peace and harmony and perform acts of generosity, as Buddha taught. In difficult times, we must all the more be compassionate to those around us, especially the poor and vulnerable.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I wish all Buddhists a blessed and peaceful Vesak Day! â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI Photo by Zinkie Aw)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on May 07, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Austrian Chancellor @sebastiankurz is hosting a series of virtual dialogues with other leaders to exchange ideas for managing COVID-19. I took part in todayâ€™s dialogue. I found it useful â€“ it helped me understand how different countries are getting ready to open up after lock downs, and what they are doing to keep people safe, from young children going to school, to close knit communities vulnerable to this very infectious disease.

An important part of opening up is keeping trade and supply lines open. Many countries have imposed export restrictions, particularly for critical supplies like drugs and medical equipment, even face masks. Others have shut down logistics nodes like ports. But it is in everyoneâ€™s interest to keep trade flowing and supply chains connected, and to rebuild confidence in the global trading system. If we can work together to strengthen international cooperation, then we can emerge stronger and more resilient after the crisis. â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on May 08, 2020. May be an image of 2 people.
text:
Heard the sad news that Mdm Woo Yun Sum has left us. She was one of five Singaporeans featured in the NDP 2018 show. The retired samsui woman was one of the Pioneer Generation who built Singapore with their determination and grit.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I shared her story at my National Day Rally that year. Her quiet resilience was captured by her matter of fact description of how the Pioneer Generation lived: æœ‰é¥­åƒé¥­ï¼Œæœ‰ç²¥åƒç²¥ (When there is rice, eat rice; when there is porridge, eat porridge).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This same resilience will help us overcome COVID-19 and sustain us to better days. May she rest in peace. èƒ¡æ¶¦å¿ƒå©†å©†ï¼Œä¸€è·¯å¥½èµ°ã€‚ â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(Photo by NDP 2018 Exco)

image_desc: Photo shared by Lee Hsien Loong on May 09, 2020 tagging @nparksbuzz.
text:
For mummies who have been working from home, the distinction between work and home has blurred. They are multitasking as housekeepers, cooks, teachers, trainers and motivators, while still doing regular jobs.

To all mothers, take heart that your efforts are deeply appreciated, and that you are loved and cherished, even if it sometimes doesnâ€™t feel like it. May you enjoy this special day with your loved ones.

Celebrations are a little different now due to COVID-19. Big family gatherings are off for now. But I am sure some of you are planning virtual celebrations, or surprising your mums creatively.

To our wonderful mothers and mothers-to-be, Happy #MothersDay! â€“ LHL (The â€œSwing Me Mamaâ€ sculpture at the Singapore Botanic Gardens, taken in 2016. / Photo by me)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on May 11, 2020. May be an image of 9 people.
text:
Happy International Nurses Day to all of our wonderful nurses! In Singapore we celebrate our own Nurses Day on 1 August, but this year I think they deserve to be celebrated more than once.â €
â €
Our healthcare workers are the backbone of our fight against COVID-19. Nurses especially, toil day and night tending to patients, and providing that crucial human touch.â €
â €
To our nurses, words are inadequate to express how grateful we are for your dedication and selflessness. You have been working hard to save lives and protect all of us. In turn, all of us will stay home and stay safe for you. â€“ LHL â €
(Speaking to some of our healthcare workers during my visit to NCID earlier in January this year. /MCI Photo by Betty Chua)

text:
Every one of us has been affected by COVID-19 in some way. The National Library Board and @natmuseum_sg are looking for contributions from individuals to document how this extraordinary and unprecedented event has impacted our daily lives.

The public can submit photos, videos, or personal accounts, or even share about our frontline heroes in our fight against COVID-19. You can contribute at these sites:

NLB: https://go.gov.sg/documenting-covid19
NMS: https://go.gov.sg/nms-ccs-covid19

Your contributions will become part of our nationâ€™s collective memory of this shared experience. COVID-19 is far from over, but I hope future generations of Singaporeans will look back, and be proud of how we, as one people, responded to this challenge of a generation. â€“ LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether

text:
Selamat Hari Raya Aidilfitri!

Esok, 1 Syawal, menandakan cukup sebulan rakan-rakan Muslim kita berpuasa. Seperti Ramadan yang berbeza kali ini, penyesuaian juga perlu dibuat bagi sambutan Hari Raya.

Biasanya, di pagi Hari Raya umat Islam akan ke masjid dan kemudian mereka kunjung-mengunjung ke rumah sanak-saudara. Namun, tahun ini, mereka akan mendengar laungan takbir Raya dah khutbah oleh Mufti Negara, menerusi radio dan media sosial dari rumah masing-masing. Jalan Raya dibuat di alam maya. Walaupun tidak bersama secara fisikal, keluarga Muslim memanfaatkan teknologi secara kreatif untuk mengeratkan tali persaudaraan dengan ahli keluarga dan teman-teman di Hari Raya ini.

Selain rancangan tahunan Suria, Sinar Lebaran yang disiarkan malam ini, Saluran 5 juga menyiarkan rancangan khas untuk mengajak rakyat Singapura yang lain sama-sama menyemarakkan lagi sambutan Hari Raya bersama masyarakat Islam kita.

Pandemik COVID-19 ini akan berlalu. Namun apa yang akan berkekalan adalah semangat Hari Raya dan harapan kita bersama untuk masa depan yang lebih cerah. Kepada semua umat Islam, semoga anda bergembira di hari mulia ini. â€“ LHL

text:
Selamat Hari Raya Aidilfitri!

Tomorrow is the first day of Syawal, which marks the end of Ramadan. Just as Ramadan was observed differently amid COVID-19, so too we have had to adjust Hari Raya celebrations.

Normally, Muslim families would be visiting the mosque tomorrow morning followed by the traditional Hari Raya visits. Instead, this year, they will join the â€˜liveâ€™ takbir on radio and online, and listen to the Hari Raya khutbah by the Mufti from their homes. Virtual visits will replace actual ones. The jalan raya will be missed; still, with creativity and technology, families have found ways to connect with loved ones and friends, and celebrate together while physically apart.

Besides the annual Hari Raya eve variety show on @mediacorp_suria tonight, @mediacorpch5 also showed a special programme, so that all Singaporeans could join in to celebrate with our Muslim friends.

This pandemic will eventually pass, but the spirit of Hari Raya will endure, and the hope of brighter days ahead. I wish all Muslim friends a joyful and blessed celebration. â€“ LHL

text:

We agreed that amidst the COVID-19 pandemic, we must continue to strengthen our cooperation, and keep markets open and supply chains connected. Happy that we are deepening our collaboration in agri-trade for the supply of rice and other food products. We will also explore reopening borders for essential travel safely and gradually, when the time is right.

text:
Glad that the late Brother Kumar (G Muthukumarasamy) has been conferred a Comrade of Labour (Star) (Bar) (Posthumous) at this yearâ€™s May Day Awards in recognition of his many contributions to workers and the labour movement. Brother Kumar was a former General Secretary of the Amalgamated Union of Public Daily Rated Workers. He passed away last November at age 68.â €
â €
Three veteran trade unionists were also conferred the Comrade of Labour (Star) (Bar) accolade, the highest award category for unionists this year â€” Brother Karthikeyan Krishnamurthy, Executive Secretary, United Workers Of Petroleum Industry; Brother Tan Hock Soon, General Secretary, Food, Drinks & Allied Workers Union; and Brother Toh Hock Poh, Consultant, Metal Industries Workers Union. All three remain involved in union work, drawing upon decades of experience to help brothers and sisters tackle current challenges.â €
â €
COVID-19 has created an extremely challenging environment for workers and businesses. We will be progressively re-opening our economy and easing circuit breaker measures after 1 June. Our tripartite partnership â€” of government, the Labour Movement and @ntucsingapore, and employers â€” must work harder and more closely than ever to support workers and businesses. Recovery will be long and hard, but I am confident that together, we can overcome our difficulties.â €
â €
Congratulations to all award recipients: go.gov.sg/mda2020citations! Thank you for your distinguished services to the unions and workers, and may it spur you on to greater contributions. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#SGUnitedâ €
#EveryWorkerMattersâ € â €
(Wefie with Brother Kumar taken at the NTUC National Delegates Conference in October 2019. / Photo by me)

text:
Our youths have been dealing with the disruptions brought about by COVID-19 in their own ways, just like all of us. The @nycsg, together with @dstnctsg, have created #DearCovid19SG, a platform for youths to share personal experiences and stories of the pandemic.

The accounts are varied â€” those who have suffered and recovered from the disease, a couple who held an e-wedding, resilient young hawkers, and some sharing their NS stories. Many are tales of overcoming adversity, while others are a call for sympathy and empathy for others.

It is a reminder that we are all in this together, and that it is good to reach out and to listen to what others are going through. If you have a COVID-19 story, why not share it with NYC? â€“ LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on June 03, 2020. May be an image of text that says 'singaporepoliceforce'.
text:
Today is Police Day. This year is a special anniversary â€” @singaporepoliceforce is celebrating 200 years since it was formed in 1820.

I was invited to the Police Day Parade that had been planned for today, and was looking forward to meeting our SPF officers and their families there. However, the parade had to be called off because of COVID-19.

Nevertheless, the SPF remains steadfast in their role as our guardians. They have also taken on new duties as part of the Ministerial Task Force on COVID-19, helping to look after our migrant workers.

My deepest appreciation to the men and women of the SPF for their commitment to safeguarding Singapore, without fear or favour, regardless of race, language or religion. â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on June 07, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Our fight against COVID-19 is the crisis of a generation. While we have made some progress, this is far from over, and we have to prepare for a very different future.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Previous generations have united, showed their mettle, and brought Singapore to what it is today. The choices that we make in this fight will define who we are as a people, and what values and ideals we pass on to future generations. Faced with adversity, we cannot yield to fear, anger or bitterness. We must not lose heart or falter.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In the next few weeks, several Ministers will address you, to share our plans for a post-COVID-19 Singapore, and how Singapore will see through this storm and emerge stronger. My Cabinet team, with the support of the whole public service, will do our best to lead us. Working as one, we can take Singapore safely through this crisis, and keep Singapore exceptional: a fair and just society where everyone can chase their dreams. Together, let us make the Singapore spirit flourish in the world.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
You can watch my address on my Facebook Page or the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

text:
Caught up with the different teams of the Inter-Agency Task Force in an e-meeting today. They have been very busy over the past several months, helping our migrant workers in the dorms during this COVID-19 pandemic.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! â€“ LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])
#SGUnited

text:
This morning, I advised President @halimahyacob to dissolve Parliament and issue the Writ of Election. Nomination Day will be on Tuesday, 30 June 2020. The Returning Officer has announced that Polling Day is on 10 July.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The road to recovery after COVID-19 will be one of Singaporeâ€™s greatest tests. To overcome the challenges ahead, we must stand completely united as one people. A general election now, when things are relatively stable, will clear the decks and give the Government a fresh five-year mandate. Then, we can focus on the agenda of recovery, and the difficult decisions that will have to be made.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Many of you are understandably concerned about safety at this time. To keep voters safe, the Elections Department will implement a number of added precautions for Polling Day. There will be more polling stations to reduce crowding. Voters will be given specific time slots for voting. Seniors will also be given priority to vote before others.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This GE will be like no other we have experienced. Not just because of the special arrangements, but also the grave issues at stake. The new Government will have critical decisions to make, which will impact and influence your lives and livelihoods. These decisions will shape Singapore for many years to come, far beyond the five-year term of the next Government. image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on June 26, 2020.
text:
Today I handed a valedictory letter to another close comrade, Minister @khawboonwan. He has been in my Cabinets since the beginning, and it is with sadness that I accepted his retirement ahead of this GE.â €
â €
Boon Wan has made immense contributions to Singapore, and left deep impressions on those he worked with, including me personally as a dear friend. In fact, it was Boon Wan who suggested in 2012 that I venture into social media. But for him you might not even be reading this here on Instagram!â €
â €
No task was ever too daunting for Boon Wan. He was in the Ministry of Health when SARS hit us. The hard lessons we learnt from SARS prepared us to deal with COVID-19. Later as the Minister he reformed MediShield and MediSave, and introduced ElderShield, thus keeping healthcare affordable for all Singaporeans. â €
â €
As Minister of National Development, he ramped up the HDB building programme, reducing BTO waiting times.â €
â €
As Transport Minister, and later Coordinating Minister for Infrastructure, Boon Wan tackled one of his biggest challenges â€“ the reliability of the MRT system. He succeeded in his own quiet and unassuming way, apparently effortlessly but actually through a prodigious amount of hard work.â €
â €
Boon Wan had a special knack of explaining nettlesome issues to Singaporeans. His colleagues could always depend on him for generous and sound advice. I am happy that he has agreed to continue sharing his experience and wisdom even after retirement. â €
â €
On behalf of all Singaporeans, and especially residents in his Sembawang constituency, I thank Boon Wan for all that he has done, and wish him a happy, healthy, and well-deserved rest. We are deeply grateful to him, and his dauntless spirit is an inspiration to us all. â€“ LHLâ € â €
(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on June 26, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
This morning, the @papsingapore launched our GE 2020 Manifesto â€” Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This is not a normal election because we are not living in normal times. The central focus of this Manifesto is how we will work together to overcome the crisis of a generation.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- How to keep Singaporeans and our migrant workers safe and prevent COVID-19 from overwhelming our healthcare system.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- How to restart and transform the economy, save jobs and businesses, and reskill workers.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- How to provide one another care and support, so that together we can keep ourselves safe amidst the uncertainties ahead.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Beyond COVID-19, this Manifesto also sets out the PAPâ€™s longer-term plans to build a better Singapore, beyond the next 5-year term of government â€” 10, 20 years down the road.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Singaporeans can rely on the PAP government. What the PAP promises, it delivers.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
We need a strong and capable leadership team, with the full support of all Singaporeans, to put our Manifesto into action. That is the way to secure our lives, our jobs, and the Future of Singapore.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
You can watch my address here on the PAP YouTube channel: www.youtube.com/PeopleActionPartyHQ â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on June 30, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
COVID-19 is the most severe crisis for humanity in a very long time. Every Singaporean has been affected by the pandemic. My Government has spared no effort to support workers, businesses and households. We have done our best to minimise the effects, but the crisis is far from over. 

Some of you have lost jobs, and many more have seen your incomes fall significantly. We are all worried by what lies ahead. We need the most capable team in charge, and a Government which has your strong mandate. Whoever leads Singapore during this crisis must have the full support of its people to make the difficult decisions needed for recovery. I ask you to entrust this responsibility once again to the @papsingapore.

My team and I will work with you to overcome this crisis of a generation. Our manifesto sets out our plans to get through this crisis safely, and then to recover strongly. Our first priority is to save jobs, and help you get back to work if youâ€™ve lost your job. All who need extra help will get it â€” be it for housing, healthcare, education or retirement. We will continue to invest in Singapore so that your children and grandchildren can look forward to a brighter future.

I will devote all my energy to this effort, as I have done for 15 years as PM. But I cannot do this alone â€“ I need your full support, and an able team of Ministers and MPs to help me. Now, more than ever, Singapore needs a capable Government, trusted to make the right decisions for all of us. Please vote for me and my PAP team. Together, we will secure our lives, our jobs, our future. â€“ LHL

text:
#GE2020 is critical. What is at stake:

- Our Lives: We are still in the thick of the fight against COVID-19 and will have to sustain this effort for perhaps a year, or longer.

- Our Jobs: The key focus of the government in the coming months and years must be jobs. We are investing heavily to reskill Singaporeans, and growing our economy to create more good jobs.

- Our Future: Even as we deal with immediate priorities of COVID-19, we must not lose sight of our longer-term mission to improve Singapore.

We will need the best possible leadership and a solidly united population to see us safely through the pandemic and economic pain, and to lead us beyond, into better days ahead.

Generations of Singaporeans have trusted in the PAP, and worked with us to build this country. Your support has been our biggest strength, and the PAP has never let you down.

I ask you once again to give me and my PAP team your mandate, so that we can face the crisis of a generation together, and carve out Singaporeâ€™s place in the world anew. â€“ LHL
 
#GE2020

text:
Glad to see events like BrainHack â€” a virtual learning fest organised by the @singaporedsta â€” carrying on despite COVID-19. Over 3,000 students from around the world signed up â€” double the number last year.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
BrainHack encourages young participants to explore the latest digital technologies. It provides hands-on training in app development, cybersecurity, artificial intelligence, space, 3D printing, and fake news detection. Many of the hackathon projects serve practical, real-world purposes and have the potential to be adopted more widely. Iâ€™m glad to see the strong interest and positive learning attitude among young people, in these challenging times!
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
BrainHack will end on this Sunday, 5 July, which coincidentally is also Youth Day. I hope such events will help youths to pick up technical skills, and more important still a passion to change the world for the better.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Wishing all BrainHack participants a fun learning experience, as well as a happy Youth Day long weekend! â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
(Photos by DSTA)

text:
A throwback to my first election in 1984, when I spoke at the @papsingaporeâ€™s lunchtime rally at Fullerton Square. 36 years later, Singapore faces a new, entirely different set of challenges. The COVID-19 pandemic has exacerbated this. Its fallout will leave a lasting impact on Singapore and the world.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This election is arguably our most critical one since independence. The next Government needs the peopleâ€™s strong support, to make difficult decisions, to lead Singapore safely through this crisis and beyond.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Every election, rain or shine, the PAP holds a lunchtime rally at Fullerton. It is the highlight of the campaign. Pandemic or no, we will again hold a Fullerton rally this time, but it will be online.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Join us tomorrow at 12 noon. I will speak about the stakes in this election, and how the PAP can meet the challenges ahead. â€“ LHL
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
#GE2020
#OurLivesOurJobsOurFuture

(PAP Rally for the 1984 General Elections at Fullerton Square. / Ministry of Information and the Arts Collection, courtesy of National Archives of Singapore)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on July 08, 2020. May be an image of 2 people.
text:
Met a Teck Ghee resident yesterday who reached into his bag to show me a blast from the past â€”Â my candidate card from my first election campaign in 1984! I had sent the card 36 years ago to his father, who had saved it all these years, and passed away just a few months ago aged 103.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
As PM, my duty is not just to keep Singapore intact through this crisis. I must also hand it over to the next generation, in good shape and into good hands. In this election, the @papsingapore has refreshed and reinforced its team with 27 new candidates. They come from many different backgrounds and experiences. They will represent you and walk with you, as we go through the difficult months and years ahead.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
#GE2020 has been an unusual campaign. With COVID-19, we could not gather and hold rallies as we usually do. Still, the virtual campaign has seen a full and serious discussion of issues, and all candidates have had ample opportunity to put forward their views to Singaporeans.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
As you reflect on the campaign on Cooling Off Day tomorrow, and cast your vote on Friday, please think about what is at stake. When you vote, you will be choosing the team that you trust, to lead us through this grave crisis, and on to a brighter future.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
My thanks to all candidates for a hard fought campaign. Thank you too to all who will be on duty on Polling Day, making sure that Singaporeans can vote safely.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Lastly, to my supporters and volunteers who have done so much to look after residents in Ang Mo Kio, and to Singaporeans who have supported me all these years in politics: thank you for sharing my journey. I hope you will elect my PAP team to continue serving you, to secure #OurLivesOurJobsOurFuture. â€“ LHLâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on July 10, 2020.
text:
Overall I am satisfied with the outcome of #GE2020. We have a clear mandate and the results show broad-based support for @papsingapore. I will use this mandate responsibly to deal with COVID-19 and the economic downturn, and to take us safely through the crisis, and beyond.â €
â €
At the same time, the results reflect the pain and uncertainty that Singaporeans feel in this crisis. This was not a feel-good election, but one where people are facing real problems, and expect more rough weather to come. There were also real concerns raised during the campaign that we must address.â €
â €
I congratulate the Workersâ€™ Party for their strong performance. I look forward to them participating in and contributing to the debate in Parliament, and to the national debate, as we deal with the urgent issues before us.â €
â €
My thanks to our PAP activists and candidates for your dedication, loyalty and hard work. Thank you also to all public officers mobilised for election duties, who ensured that Singaporeans could vote safely during this unprecedented GE. Finally, thank you to all voters for your patience and understanding. My team will continue to serve Singaporeans, whichever party you voted for.â €
â €
The work of the new government begins today. My government will work with all Singaporeans to overcome our challenges and emerge stronger. With this election behind us, let us now work as one Singapore, to secure Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on July 10, 2020.
text:
Overall I am satisfied with the outcome of #GE2020. We have a clear mandate and the results show broad-based support for @papsingapore. I will use this mandate responsibly to deal with COVID-19 and the economic downturn, and to take us safely through the crisis, and beyond.â €
â €
At the same time, the results reflect the pain and uncertainty that Singaporeans feel in this crisis. This was not a feel-good election, but one where people are facing real problems, and expect more rough weather to come. There were also real concerns raised during the campaign that we must address.â €
â €
I congratulate the Workersâ€™ Party for their strong performance. I look forward to them participating in and contributing to the debate in Parliament, and to the national debate, as we deal with the urgent issues before us.â €
â €
My thanks to our PAP activists and candidates for your dedication, loyalty and hard work. Thank you also to all public officers mobilised for election duties, who ensured that Singaporeans could vote safely during this unprecedented GE. Finally, thank you to all voters for your patience and understanding. My team will continue to serve Singaporeans, whichever party you voted for.â €
â €
The work of the new government begins today. My government will work with all Singaporeans to overcome our challenges and emerge stronger. With this election behind us, let us now work as one Singapore, to secure Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on July 10, 2020.
text:
Overall I am satisfied with the outcome of #GE2020. We have a clear mandate and the results show broad-based support for @papsingapore. I will use this mandate responsibly to deal with COVID-19 and the economic downturn, and to take us safely through the crisis, and beyond.â €
â €
At the same time, the results reflect the pain and uncertainty that Singaporeans feel in this crisis. This was not a feel-good election, but one where people are facing real problems, and expect more rough weather to come. There were also real concerns raised during the campaign that we must address.â €
â €
I congratulate the Workersâ€™ Party for their strong performance. I look forward to them participating in and contributing to the debate in Parliament, and to the national debate, as we deal with the urgent issues before us.â €
â €
My thanks to our PAP activists and candidates for your dedication, loyalty and hard work. Thank you also to all public officers mobilised for election duties, who ensured that Singaporeans could vote safely during this unprecedented GE. Finally, thank you to all voters for your patience and understanding. My team will continue to serve Singaporeans, whichever party you voted for.â €
â €
The work of the new government begins today. My government will work with all Singaporeans to overcome our challenges and emerge stronger. With this election behind us, let us now work as one Singapore, to secure Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

Took a #jalanjalan around Ang Mo Kio Central to thank residents for voting for my team in this GE. My team and I are humbled by your support, and will do our best to look after all of you! 

Todayâ€™s walk was a nice change of pace compared to the hectic schedule of campaign walkabouts. I had time to take some shots of the hawkers â€“ their wares looked mouth-watering!

Now that the dust is settling after the hustings, I am looking forward to getting back to the task at hand â€”Â navigating Singapore through the COVID-19 crisis. â€“ LHL

text:
This yearâ€™s National Day celebrations will be different from what weâ€™ve been used to. It will be a quieter and more sombre affair due to COVID-19. We will hold a scaled-down Parade at the Padang, and Singaporeans can still look forward to their favourite segments like the Red Lions and mobile column taking place in other parts of the island.â €
â €
And of course, we still have an #NDP2020 theme song. Sung by @nathanhartono, this yearâ€™s music video features scenes showcasing the stories of Singaporeans who have selflessly contributed during these tough times. Other stories will be featured during the NDP morning and evening shows.â €
â €
The themes of togetherness, kindness and gratitude in the song are not new, but during this season, they are all the more important. Let us continue to reach out to one another, to help those in need, and to work together to build our home - the sea of shining crystals in the sand. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
#OurHeartforSGâ €
#TogetherStrongerSGâ €
#ndpeeps

text:
Today I announced my new Cabinet line-up. This is a team with a good mix of experience and ideas that will bring us through the COVID-19 crisis and beyond.â €
â €
It has the experienced senior members, tempered by the many challenges they have gone through.â €
â €
It has younger Ministers â€“ @hengsweekeat, Chan Chun Sing, and the others, who are increasingly setting the agenda, and preparing to take over from me and my older colleagues. â €
â €
It is reinforced by new members who will bring different perspectives, fresh ideas and energy to take us forward.â €
â €
Singapore is in the midst of a battle that will define our generation. While we have made much progress, the road ahead is long. I ask Singaporeans to give me and my team your full support. We will work with you to secure Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photos by Lee Jia Wen)

text:
Was sworn-in together with my new Cabinet at the Istana and Parliament House yesterday. This is the first time the ceremony was held in split locations, because of COVID-19.

My team and I are humbled that Singaporeans have entrusted us with this heavy responsibility. We will continue to do our best for Singapore. With your mandate, I have formed the strongest Cabinet I could, to take Singapore through this crisis and beyond. We will use our mandate to act on your behalf, to deal with the challenges ahead, and lead Singapore out of the crisis.
Â 
I have spent my entire adult life in public service and I will continue to devote myself to Singapore. My aim is to see through this crisis, and hand over Singapore, into good hands who can take the country further forward.Â Â 
Â 
Let us now all come together as one Singapore, unite and focus our energies on the major challenges ahead. Keep improving our lives, securing our future and building a nation we can all be proud to call home. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by Chwee [1,2] and Fyrol [3])

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on July 28, 2020. May be an image of 2 people.
text:
Enjoyed my virtual dialogue with David Rubenstein and the @atlanticcouncil last night. The Atlantic Council is an American think tank that focuses on international affairs, and I was grateful for the opportunity to share our perspectives on global issues. We spoke on a great variety of topics, from US-China tensions, developments in Hong Kong, and how Singapore is dealing with the COVID-19 pandemic.

While the pandemic has forced many countries to turn inwards and focus on domestic issues, we must also remember that we are still friends and partners with the rest of the world. You can watch our discussion from last night on the PMO YouTube channel (link in my profile). â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

text:
Today, Singapore and Malaysia formally agreed to resume the Johor Bahru - Singapore Rapid Transit System (RTS) Link Project.

The project has been suspended since last April, partly because of political transitions in Malaysia, and partly because of COVID-19. Officials on both sides put in many months of hard work into the intense negotiations, in order to complete the revised agreements. Work can now at last resume.

The RTS Link is a valuable project to both sides. It will improve connectivity and people-to-people ties between Singapore and Johor. Once operational, it will ease congestion on the Causeway. So it was apt that we marked this milestone with a bilateral ceremony at the Causeway, which has connected our two countries for almost a hundred years.

The pandemic has shown how deeply entwined our two countries are. Even in these difficult times, we continue to work together, and look forward to doing still more together. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by Lee Jiawen)

text:
National Day celebrations have started! ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬

Joined President @halimahyacob and PMO staff at the Istana National Day Observance Ceremony. @teocheehean, Tharman Shanmugaratnam, and many of our staff from the PMO agencies joined in virtually. It was a small, quiet affair compared to previous years, and this year we sang Majulah Singapura and recited our Pledge in our hearts, but not aloud, because of COVID-19, which only made it a more heartfelt and poignant ceremony.

As we enjoy the long weekend and festivities with family and friends, let us also think about all those doing their best to keep Singapore going during these difficult times. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on August 08, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Every 9 August since independence, rain or shine, in good years and difficult ones, we have come together for the National Day Parade, to celebrate the birth of our nation, and renew our commitment to Singapore.

This year, despite COVID-19, we are still holding the Parade â€” as a symbol of our solidarity, and also to salute those on our frontline, fighting the pandemic.

We need our unity and resilience now more than ever. As we have seen in other countries, the danger of a resurgence of cases is ever present. We also need to be resilient in the face of the severe economic downturn. Let us brace ourselves for the trials ahead, so that many years from now, when our grandchildren celebrate National Day, they will look back and say that this generation stood together, sacrificed for one another, and built Singapore together.

Let us show the world that whatever the challenges, Singaporeans will stay united, and prevail once more.

I wish all Singaporeans a very happy National Day! ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬Â 

You can watch the my National Day Message in all four languages on the PMO Youtube channel (click on the link in my profile).Â 

â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on August 08, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
Every 9 August since independence, rain or shine, in good years and difficult ones, we have come together for the National Day Parade, to celebrate the birth of our nation, and renew our commitment to Singapore.

This year, despite COVID-19, we are still holding the Parade â€” as a symbol of our solidarity, and also to salute those on our frontline, fighting the pandemic.

We need our unity and resilience now more than ever. As we have seen in other countries, the danger of a resurgence of cases is ever present. We also need to be resilient in the face of the severe economic downturn. Let us brace ourselves for the trials ahead, so that many years from now, when our grandchildren celebrate National Day, they will look back and say that this generation stood together, sacrificed for one another, and built Singapore together.

Let us show the world that whatever the challenges, Singaporeans will stay united, and prevail once more.

I wish all Singaporeans a very happy National Day! ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬Â 

You can watch the my National Day Message in all four languages on the PMO Youtube channel (click on the link in my profile).Â 

â€“ LHL

text:
Very happy to welcome Japan Foreign Minister Motegi Toshimitsu to the Istana today â€” he is my first foreign visitor since the pandemic led to entry restrictions and border closures. We had a good discussion on how we can do more together as we deal with the pandemic.

Japan is one of the countries with whom we are discussing setting up reciprocal â€˜green lanesâ€™, to resume essential travel with the necessary safety precautions. We are proceeding cautiously, as COVID-19 is still very much a threat. But this will be an important step forward in restoring connectivity between countries, and adjusting to life with COVID-19. â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on August 20, 2020.
text:
Welcomed another foreign visitor to the Istana today. Despite the ongoing pandemic, itâ€™s a good feeling to return to some semblance of normalcy.
 
Had a fruitful meeting with Communist Party of China Politburo member and Central Commission for Foreign Affairs Office Director Yang Jiechi. As you would expect, we discussed our respective COVID-19 situations. Despite the pandemic, both sides have kept up contacts through phone and video calls. Singapore and China had earlier agreed on a â€œfast laneâ€ for essential business and official travel between both countries. At the moment this covers six Chinese provinces and municipalities, and hopefully this list will grow if the situation stays under control.

This year marks the 30th anniversary of Singapore-China diplomatic relations. Our ties with China are substantial and multi-faceted. I am confident that by working with each other and with the international community, we can make more progress in the post-COVID world. â€“ LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

text:
The 14th Parliament was sworn in yesterday at Parliament House and the Arts House. In her opening address, President @halimahyacob emphasised the need for our new generation of leaders and Singaporeans to work together to overcome COVID-19, and the worst recession we are facing since independence.Â 

She laid out five priorities in this new term of government: â€¨1. Secure jobs for Singaporeans; â€¨2. Build a fair and just society; â€¨3. Strengthen our Singaporean identity; â€¨4. Evolve our politics; andÂ 
5. Build a â€˜Singapore Togetherâ€™ spirit in the next phase of nation building.

MPs will debate the Presidentâ€™s speech next week, and I will be speaking in the debate.

These are uncertain times, and we will have to continue adapting to major changes in the world. We must remain united â€“ as one people together with our elected government â€“ to survive and thrive despite these challenges, and secure a brighter future for ourselves and future generations. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by Zinkie Aw [1,3] and Betty Chua [2])

text:

â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
I am sorry to learn that Japanese Prime Minister @shinzoabe has resigned from office for health reasons.

I have worked well with Mr Abe for close to nine years. Under his leadership, our bilateral relations have deepened. We last met in person in November, and more recently online in April, during the virtual ASEAN Plus Three Summit on COVID-19.

Mr Abe also played a critical role in concluding the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CPTPP) after the US left the original Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations.

I wish Abe-san a good recovery as he begins treatment for his condition. â€“ LHL

(At the 2019 G20 Summit in Osaka. / MCI Photo by Chwee)

text:
Gave my first speech of this Parliament this afternoon. Each first Parliament sitting is a valuable opportunity to take stock of how we have done so far, what has gotten us here, and what our immediate priorities are.
â €
This time, our work is cut out for us â€“ not only to deal with the immediate threat of COVID-19, but also to plan for an uncertain new future in its wake. â €
â €
In this climate of economic uncertainty, it is only natural to feel anxious about our social support, and competition from foreigners. I want to reassure Singaporeans that the Government will always be on your side. This is why we are adjusting our work pass schemes, and tightening the Fair Consideration Framework. However, please remember that we must stay open to the world, to attract businesses to set up here, and in turn create good jobs and opportunities for Singaporeans. â €
â €
During the clarifications, I explained the mindset we should have in elections. Voters are choosing the party they wish to govern Singapore; your vote matters. Vote because you truly support the party, whether PAP or opposition, and not because you want â€˜the best of both worldsâ€™. â €
â €
Singaporean voters have spoken, and I respect their choice. The Government will do its part to work with the opposition to keep Parliament a constructive forum for debate. â €
â €
Singapore has survived many life or death crises before. Each time we survived, and came back stronger. Like all previous crises, COVID-19 will be the occasion for us to do better, emerge stronger, and more united than before. 
â €
You can watch my full speech on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(PMO Video by Alex Qiu & Chiez How)
