COVID-19 has upended our lives, not least for teachers and students. This was most felt during the circuit breaker, when schools and institutes of higher learning shifted to full home-based learning.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Within a short time, teachers had to pick up new skills and play new roles, while coming up with ways to engage students during lessons â€” on top of juggling their own family arrangements and working from home themselves. Parents too, got a taste of a teacherâ€™s role and challenges during the full home-based learning period.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Here's to all our wonderful teachers â€” for your selfless effort, care and commitment towards your students, especially during this pandemic. I wish you all a Happy Teachersâ€™ Day! â€“ LHL

text:
Today marks one year since the official opening of the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID) at @tantocksenghospital.

Never was the opening of a medical facility so timely and fortuitous, as NCID found itself at the forefront of our fight against COVID-19 just a few months later.Â 

We were lucky that NCID was up and running before COVID-19 hit us, but this did not happen by chance. It was the result of years of planning and hard work by government agencies, medical and research institutions, and healthcare partners. Without this, our response to the pandemic would have been very different.

NCID, and all our medical and healthcare institutions and workers, remain our first line of defence against the pandemic. Our situation is stable for now, but the battle is far from won. Let us each continue to do our part by staying vigilant and socially responsible. Congratulations and happy birthday, NCID! â€“ LHL

(Visit to NCID in January 2020./ MCI Photo by Betty Chua)

text:
[1/4] The debate on the Presidentâ€™s Address ended last Friday. Many MPs, experienced and new, stood up to speak on a wide variety of issues. My Ang Mo Kio teammates did their part: 

@samdingoingon gave a heartfelt speech about helping the â€œsandwiched classâ€ and vulnerable families, as well as how individuals of different generations should find common ground.

You can watch the other three speeches by Gan Thiam Poh, Ng Ling Ling and @darryldavid_sg on my IGTV. 

Four very different speeches in style and subject matter, but bound by a common conviction to improve the lives of Singaporeans.

Our immediate priority is the COVID-19 situation. But as Nadia said, â€œIn times of hardship such as this, we need to sow seeds of hope for when the rain passes, and a strong vision for the future.â€ 

The government will continue to help those affected by the pandemic, but we must not neglect our long term plans to ensure a good future for all Singaporeans. After rain, we want to emerge stronger to a more hopeful and forward-looking Singapore. â€“ LHL

text:
Met the team from the Assurance, Care and Engagement (ACE) Group today. The ACE Group is a new division in the Ministry of Manpower. It takes over from the Inter-agency Task Force (ITF), which has been doing COVID-19 operations in the migrant worker dormitories since April.â €
 â €
I am grateful to the ACE and ITF teams for their hard work. They have been testing our migrant workers, plus delivering meals, providing medical care, keeping them safe and finally bringing the dorm outbreak well under control. It has been an enormous task, on a scale beyond what most Singaporeans are aware of.â €
 â €
We are now transitioning to a more permanent arrangement with ACE. The migrant workers are returning to work. We have to ensure that they can work safely, live safely, and rest safely, to prevent COVID-19 from coming back. We need support from employers, dorm operators, management, and non-government organisations. We also ask for the understanding of the migrant workers themselves, as we strive to keep them safe and well.â €
â €
Thank you all once again for the good work! â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

text:
Even as we fight COVID-19, we cannot take our eyes off other threats. We are redoubling our efforts to combat dengue, and one way is to use mosquitoes against themselves.

I visited the @nea_sg â€“ Environmental Health Institute (EHI) Mosquito Production Facility yesterday. Project Wolbachia involves the release of Wolbachia bacteria-carrying male Aedes aegypti mosquitoes. The Aedes aegypti mosquito is the primary vector that spreads dengue. When the released male Wolbachia mosquitoes mate with urban female Aedes aegypti that do not carry Wolbachia, their eggs donâ€™t hatch. This reduces the mosquito population, and the risk of dengue transmission. 

I learned about various technologies under development that will allow EHI to efficiently produce and release large numbers of Wolbachia-Aedes mosquitoes. Project Wolbachia is a collaborative effort: EHI works closely with local and international partners, including Orinno Technology, Ngee Ann Polytechnic, Verily Life Sciences, and the International Atomic Energy Agency to develop such technologies.

Wolbachia-Aedes mosquito suppression is just one of the ways we are fighting dengue. All of us have an important part to play in helping to destroy mosquito breeding habitats, all over Singapore. Hope you havenâ€™t forgotten how to do the Mozzie Wipeout!

#ProjectWolbachiaSG is one of the EHIâ€™s many projects. They also monitor air quality as well as conduct environmental surveillance. Their waste water surveillance programme has an important role in monitoring the spread of COVID-19. My thanks to NEA, EHI and their partners for their efforts in keeping us safe. â€“ LHL

([1, 3-6] MCI Photos by Lee Jia Wen; [2] Photo by me)

text:
Held separate virtual meetings with the advisory panels of the Economic Development Board (EDB) and the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) over the past two evenings.Â 

The panels comprise leaders of MNCs and financial institutions from across the globe, who advise the EDB and MAS on our strategies. Singapore has a reputation for being open and pro-business, and our regular dialogues help keep us in touch with what businesses are focused on, as well as trends we need to watch.Â 

We had a lot to discuss this year â€“ sustainability, geopolitics, US-China tensions, nationalist tendencies, and whether or not COVID-19 would result in a â€˜new normalâ€™ or â€˜old ++â€™. Some noted that with working from home becoming a necessity, having capable island-wide technological infrastructure is one of Singaporeâ€™s advantages in a post-COVID world.Â 

I am grateful to EDB and MAS, as well as all the members of both panels, for helping Singapore to keep moving forward in an uncertain world. â€“ LHL
Â 
([1] Dialogue with EDBâ€™s International Advisory Council. / MCI Photo by Fyrol; [2] Dialogue with the MAS International Advisory Panel. / MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

text:
Presented @lowyenling.sg, @denisephua, @desmond.choo, @zayam and @fahmialimansg with their Certificates of Appointment and Mayoral Badges at the Mayorsâ€™ swearing-in ceremony today. Alex and Fahmi take over from Teo Ho Pin and @maliki_osman, who are stepping down after many years of leadership and contributions.

Our Mayors are chairpersons of the Community Development Councils (CDCs) for the five respective districts. The CDCs play an important role in our social support system. They not only implement government programmes, but also serve as eyes and ears on the ground. They connect with communities, and identify emerging needs and gaps in social support. CDCs deliver services with a human touch, in a way that government agencies that operate on a national scale find harder to do. 

CDCs work quietly to fulfil their mission, but in times of crisis, their contributions are vital. Since COVID-19, the CDCs have rolled out more than 70 initiatives. The CDC Vouchers Scheme is a good example. The five CDCs launched this community scheme to help 400,000 households defray the cost of living, while supporting local businesses through the COVID-19 period.
 
Congratulations to all five Mayors on their appointments. I wish them every success in their new term! 

You can watch my speech on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by Lee Jia Wen)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on October 02, 2020. May be an image of 2 people, people standing, suit and outerwear.
text:
Today marks 30 years of diplomatic relations between Singapore and China. Our relationship started even before formal establishment of diplomatic ties in 1990, and our bilateral collaboration has deepened and expanded over the years.
Â 
China has been our largest trading partner and we have been Chinaâ€™s largest foreign investor since 2013. People-to-people exchanges have also grown. In 2018 more than four million people travelled between our countries â€“ 40 times as many as the 100,000 travellers in 1990. COVID-19 has suspended the flights for now, but amid the pandemic, we have continued to support each other, and embarked on new areas of cooperation. Beyond bilateral ties, we have also worked well together in regional and international fora.
Â 
I look forward to growing and strengthening our ties and bringing our partnership to greater heights. â€“ LHL

(Premier Li Keqiang made an official visit to Singapore in November 2018. / MCI Photo by LH Goh)

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on October 08, 2020. May be an image of one or more people and people sitting.
text:
Happy to welcome Australian Foreign Minister @marise.payne to the Istana today.

This is our first in-person meeting with Australia since the outbreak started. But we have been keeping in touch through video conferences and phone calls, such as my meeting with PM @scottmorrisonmp for the 5th Singapore-Australia Virtual Leadersâ€™ Meeting in March.

This year also marks the 5th anniversary of the signing of the Comprehensive Strategic Partnership (CSP). Despite the COVID-19 disruptions we have made significant progress in key areas of cooperation under the CSP.

Minister Payne and I had a good discussion on how we can do more together amid the pandemic. Our relations with Australia are substantial and multifaceted. I am confident that we will deepen our partnership further in the future. â€“ LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

text:
Itâ€™s been an unusual year for our kids. COVID-19 has disrupted school and upended familiar routines.

Parents know how resilient children can be, but it still makes us proud to see how bravely and responsibly our young ones have adapted â€“ wearing masks in classrooms, getting used to home-based learning, forgoing birthday parties with friends, and celebrating the usual festivals and events, like Childrenâ€™s Day, a little differently.

This yearâ€™s edition of the annual photo contest by @moesingapore, â€œOur Schools, Our Storiesâ€, captures images of school life before and after COVID-19. A roving exhibition of the winning photos is going to 7 locations around the island until 1 March 2021. Do catch it if you can!

The pandemic has turned out to be the biggest and most important lesson this year for our children. I think everyone deserves an A+ for your response!

I wish everyone a very happy Childrenâ€™s Day! â€“ LHL

text:
10 October is World Mental Health Day. The @WHO held an online advocacy event yesterday to raise awareness, and I shared a few words on what we are doing in Singapore.

Ensuring access to quality mental healthcare for every citizen is a major priority for us. COVID-19 has made this especially vital, as more people face stresses, pressures and disruptions to their lives and livelihoods. Weâ€™ve set up a National CARE Hotline (1800-202-6868) and a COVID-19 Mental Wellness Taskforce, to help all those who need it.

One of the biggest hurdles dealing with mental health problems is the stigma. But this is also why the best and most reliable support system is the people around us. If we know someone having a tough time, even a simple â€œhow are you?â€ is a good way to show we care, and to reassure them itâ€™s okay to talk about their problems.Â 

In Singapore, 1 in 7 will suffer from a mental health condition at some point in their lives. Just as we take care of each othersâ€™ physical health by wearing masks, let us also work together to understand mental health better, to care for one another during these difficult times. â€“ LHL
Â 
(PMO Video by Alex Qiu)

text:
Took part in a virtual dialogue with senior leaders across AsiaÂ organised by @mckinseyco this morning.

The theme was â€œReimagining the next normal for Asia and the Worldâ€. I shared what we have been doing to see Singapore through this COVID-19 pandemic.Â 

To wrap up our discussion, moderator Oliver Tonby, Chairman of McKinsey & Company Asia, asked for my views on good leadership.Â 

My answer: a good leader must muster a capable team that you can trust, and tap on others who know more than you. You must also be psychologically prepared for surprises and setbacks, and make the best decision based on the knowledge you have. Above all, focus on your responsibilities and fulfil your duty to your people, regardless of any personal consequences to yourself. â€“ LHL
Â 
(MCI Photo by Terence Tan)

text:
Happy to attend my first â€˜onlineâ€™ groundbreaking ceremony today. It was for the Hyundai Motor Group Innovation Centre in Singapore (HMGICS). Set to open in 2022, this facility will be the first of its kind. It will develop automotive technologies, and manufacture electric vehicles to export around the world. This will help steer us towards our goal to have all vehicles run on cleaner energy by 2040.â €
â €
The HMGICS will also create more jobs for Singaporeans, especially cutting edge roles that will require new skills. COVID-19 has shown the need to integrate technology into more aspects of our lives, whether work or leisure. Climate change, too, is a longer-term issue that we must take action on. The new facility will help us address both issues.â €
â €
Iâ€™m happy to see our relationship with Hyundai deepen. I am confident that Hyundaiâ€™s vision and ambition â€“ to push the limits of what is possible â€“ will make this project a success. May this pave the way for deeper partnerships with our friends from Korea! â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photos by Terence Tan)

text:
I was moved by these stories of public officers who went above and beyond to help others when the COVID-19 first hit us. Despite the challenges of dealing with multiple unknowns, fluid circumstances and personal sacrifices, they rose to the occasion and gave their best.

We have stabilised our COVID-19 situation by dint of an immense effort. As of yesterday, there were no locally transmitted cases since March. But the battle goes on. Public officers in various agencies continue to monitor developments here and abroad closely, and be ready to respond quickly and take action to support communities and businesses, and curb the spread of the virus.Â 

@gov.sg worked with four local filmmakers â€“ @relaxlahtariqq, @jonathan77, @elliengim, and K.Rajagopal â€“ to produce these four short films, in commemoration of Public Service Week 2020. You can view them at: http://go.gov.sg/as-oneÂ 

My heartfelt thanks to all in our Public Service for your dedication and commitment! â€“ LHL

text:
Today, we held a virtual Public Service Observance Ceremony. In my message, I thanked public officers for their dedication and efforts during this crisis. Many dealt with situations out of their comfort zone â€“ serving on the frontlines, in hospitals, migrant workersâ€™ dormitories, and at the border. Others worked long hours from offices and homes, to come up with solutions to the disruptions caused by the pandemic, from schools to businesses, travel and our vulnerable groups.â €
â €
There were inevitably shortcomings to our COVID-19 response. We will learn from them, improve our processes and do better. But as we adjusted and strengthened our responses to the pandemic, our officers rose to the occasion, and pulled together as one public service.â €
â €
I hope you will join me in saluting our public officers. Without them, we wouldnâ€™t have got thus far. The fight is not over, the battle is far from won. But together, we will overcome. â€“ LHLâ €
 â €
(PMO Video by Alex Qiu)â €
â €
@psdsingapore

text:
Met my Ang Mo Kio Town team for our annual dialogue, albeit virtually across 7 CCs! This is the first time the new team (AMK GRC + Yio Chu Kang + Kebun Baru) and our grassroots leaders all came together since the elections.

It was a candid and open discussion on helping our residents respond to COVID-19 and its impact on their lives, and how global events would affect Singapore. As a small country, we have to be attuned to happenings around us to safeguard our interests, and keep an eye out for new opportunities to steer Singapore forward. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photos by Terence Tan)

text:
A big thank you to Maestro Tsung Yeh and the @singaporechineseorchestra for the lovely medleys at our virtual annual fundraising gala concert last night! This yearâ€™s programme was inspired by the yueqin æœˆç´. The thoughtfully put together showcase of beloved classics and familiar favourites made for an enjoyable musical evening. Mrs Goh-Tan Choo Leng also serenaded us to a selection of 1980s classics, featuring ä¸€å‰ªæ¢… (A Spray of Plum Blossoms) and æ˜å¤©ä¼šæ›´å¥½ (Tomorrow Will Be Better).â €
â €
Those in the arts scene have been among the most affected by COVID-19. By using technology, the SCO and many other groups have managed to give live performances and connect with their audiences. You can find SCOâ€™s past concert productions #DabaoSCO and other exciting content on their social media platforms, and on Spotify too!â €
â €
Many thanks as well to the donors. Your generosity during this tough time is a lifeline for SCO. You have enabled the orchestra to continue reaching their audiences, and bring comfort and joy to all through their music. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

text:
â€œWho would be mad enough to invest in Singapore in a recession?â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
During the 1985 economic crisis, the Economic Development Board placed a full page ad in the Wall Street Journal with this eye-catching headline. Nine global MNC heads signed and endorsed this message.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Now, at another hinge in our history, EDB is again sending a bold message to the world.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Singapore has survived many crises before. As on previous occasions, COVID-19 will give us a chance to do better, emerge stronger, and show what makes us an exceptional nation.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Whatever the challenges, we will prevail, and the little red dot will continue to shine brightly. â€“ LHL

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on November 08, 2020. May be an image of 2 people, people standing, outerwear and suit.
text:
Congratulations to President-elect @joebiden and Vice President-elect @kamalaharris!

The COVID-19 pandemic has brought on serious challenges for every country, including the United States and Singapore. At this critical time, the duty of a leader is to unite the people, strengthen their trust in the government, and see the nation through the crisis.

With his long history and deep experience as a former US Vice President and US Senator, Mr Biden is well-placed to lead his country through the challenges ahead.

Mr Biden is familiar with the USâ€™ long-standing, multifaceted and robust partnership with Singapore. As Vice President, he visited Singapore in 2013. Three years later, when I visited Washington D.C. in August 2016, he made time to host me to lunch too.

Mr Biden, Singapore looks forward to working with you and your Administration to deepen the partnership between our two countries, enhance the USâ€™ role in Asia-Pacific, and overcome COVID-19. You can count on Singapore to remain a friend and partner. â€“ LHL

(Mr Biden met me at the Oval Office so that we could walk over to his office together. Taken during my visit to the White House in 2013. / PMO Photo by Alex Qiu)

text:
How has COVID-19 changed the way we look at the world? John Micklethwait, Bloombergâ€™s Editor-in-chief, asked me this during my interview for their New Economy Forum.

My answer was simple: COVID-19 is a powerful reminder that while Man proposes, God disposes. Immediately, governments worldwide were forced to change gears, put aside their plans, and make COVID-19 their top priority. It was a stark lesson that no matter how carefully one plans ahead, being able to deal with the unexpected is equally important. â€“ LHL

(MCI Photo by Fyrol)

text:

We canâ€™t travel overseas for a while yet. I hope you will take a closer look and â€œrediscoverâ€ the sights and sounds of Singapore, particularly with the SingapoRediscovers vouchers available from next month. However you choose to spend your break, I wish you a safe and healthy holiday period! â€“ LHLâ €

text:
Since G20 Summit participants could not meet in person in Riyadh, this yearâ€™s host created a virtual family photo instead. Yet another way the world is adjusting to life with COVID-19.

Although not a G20 member, Singapore has been invited again as a guest country to this yearâ€™s virtual gathering. Look forward to fruitful discussions over the weekend on collective efforts to overcome the pandemic, restore growth and jobs, and build an inclusive, sustainable and resilient future. â€“ LHL
 
(The G20 Riyadh Summit virtual family photo, projected on the walls of At-Turaif District in Ad-Diriyah, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. / Photo courtesy of @g20org)

In some years, the @apec Economic Leaders Meeting (AELM) takes place back-to-back with the #G20 Summit. There are common participants between the two meetings. APEC is a forum of 21 Asia-Pacific economies including Singapore, while the G20 comprises 19 major economies and the European Union. Singapore is an invited guest country of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to this yearâ€™s G20 Summit. Top of the agenda was COVID-19 and how we can overcome the pandemic and restore growth and jobs. â€“ LHLâ €

Had a video call with Malaysian PM @muhyiddinyassin_official earlier this evening to discuss the KL-Singapore High Speed Rail (HSR) project. The project is currently suspended, until 31 December 2020.

text:
Addressing the German Parliament, Chancellor Angela Merkel made an impassioned plea to her people to adhere to tougher restrictions to stem the rising tide of COVID-19 infections in the country.Â 

In Singapore, the number of new cases has stayed low, but we must not let our guard down. The battle is far from over. We must all continue to do our part and stay vigilant. We must not let our hard won successes slip away. â€“ LHL

text:

â €
My speech will be livestreamed on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) at 5pm on Monday, 14 December. You can also catch it live on @mediacorp TV channels and radio. Do tune in! â €
â €
But please stay calm â€“ no need to stock up on anything! â€“ LHLâ €

text:
2020 has been a difficult year for Singapore and the world. COVID-19 continues to defy global efforts to overcome it. Grateful that we can be with our loved ones this season. Our thoughts too for those who have lost family and friends.

image_desc: Photo by Lee Hsien Loong on December 31, 2020. May be an image of flower, tree and nature.
text:
2021 brings hope that the darkest days of 2020 are behind us. That we are in a good situation now, and able to gather and celebrate the start of the new year in small groups, is the result of enormous effort and sacrifice.â€¨â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â€¨A new generation has shown we have what it takes to make our small island nation survive and succeed, but the fight against COVID-19 is not yet won. In the months and years ahead, we will face new and unexpected hurdles. Things may happen that force us to change our plans. But so long as we stay together as one Singapore, I am confident we will blaze a path forward.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Happy New Year, Singapore! Stay safe, and stay strong. You can read my New Year Message for 2021 here: go.gov.sg/nym2021 â€“ LHL

text:
Wrote to @potus Joe Biden and @vp Kamala Harris to congratulate them on their swearing-in yesterday. â €
â €
Mr Biden takes office at a time when many pressing challenges confront the US and the rest of the world, not least dealing with COVID-19. Strong American leadership will decisively contribute to our collective recovery, and the shape of the post-pandemic world. â €
â €
This US election was contentious and bitter. I wish Mr Biden every success in his endeavours to heal the divisions. National Youth Poet Laureate Amanda Gorman put it beautifully in her poem she recited at the inauguration: â€œSo we lift our gazes not to what stands between us, but what stands before us. We close the divide because we know to put our future first, we must first put our differences aside. We lay down our arms so we can reach out our arms to one another, we seek harm to none and harmony for all.â€â €
â €
Singapore has been a long-standing strategic, defence and economic partner of the US. I look forward to working with Mr Biden and his Administration to strengthen Americaâ€™s engagement of Asia and ASEAN. I hope to meet him face-to-face as soon as we are able to, either in Singapore or Washington DC. â€“ LHLâ €
â €
(Catching up with then-Vice President Joe Biden during my visit to the White House in 2013. / PMO Photo by Alex Qiu)

It is our second Chinese New Year since COVID-19 first came to Singapore. Weâ€™ve been through much since then, but can still take comfort in familiar customs and practices, and look forward to the Year of the Ox with confidence and hope. This @gov.sg video is a lighthearted take on how our lives have changed, and the importance of family and community support.

text:
Visited the @singaporeair Cabin Crew Control Centre at @changiairport T3 and Changi General Hospital (@cghsg)Â this morning, to bring festive cheer and thank their teams for keeping Singapore going, not just today on Chinese New Year, but every single day of the year.Â 

Healthcare and aviation have had a tough year because of COVID-19. As we celebrate the festive season (safely) with our families and friends, let us remember to thank workers â€“ from frontline and essential services, to transport and retail, and many more â€“ whose hard work allows so many others to enjoy the holiday. Wishing everyone good health and contentment in the year ahead! ç¥å¤§å®¶æ–°å¹´å¿«ä¹ï¼Œå¹¸ç¦ç¾æ»¡ï¼â€“ LHL

Each household to receive utilities rebates between $120 and $200 this year S&CC rebates extended fora year to households -Top-up of $200 per child through CDA, Edusave, Post- Secondary EducationAccounts EdunA $100 CDC vouchers per household MOF mof_sg BUDGET 2021'.
text:
As DPM @hengsweekeat announced in his #SGBudget2021 speech today, the FY2020 budget deficit was 13.9% of GDP, the largest ever. This was what we needed, to keep Singaporeans safe and protect their livelihoods during COVID-19.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
This year, we will continue to help Singaporeans and businesses through the $11 billion COVID-19 Resilience Package. Although we are again running a deficit, it is much smaller â€“ only 2.2% of GDP. Things are gradually returning to normal.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
While grappling with the pandemic, we must not neglect the future. Hence the Budget has many items that build our capabilities and competitiveness. When the sun shines again, we must be ready to seize the new opportunities.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
This â€œcan doâ€ spirit helped us overcome the last financial crisis. With the resilience that our people have shown this time, I am confident that we can do it again.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
Find out more about the Budget here: www.singaporebudget.gov.sg
â €â €â €â €â €â €
â€“ LHLâ €â €â €â €â €â €
